'''George Carter''' (dates unknown) was an English [[cricket]]er who played in [[first-class cricket]] during the 1740s, chiefly associated with [[London Cricket Club]]. He is first recorded playing for London in a [[single wicket cricket|single wicket]] match at the [[Artillery Ground]] on Monday, 22 August 1748.<ref>Ashley-Cooper, p.52.</ref> Carter took part in two more single wicket contests in 1749, both played for high stakes, and was then a member of [[Robert Colchin|Long Robin's XI]] against [[Tom Faulkner|Tom Faulkner's XI]] at the Artillery Ground on Monday, 28 August 1749.<ref>Ashley-Cooper, p.67.</ref>
As Carter had established his reputation by 1748, he must have been active for some years previously and his career may have begun in the 1730s. Very few players were mentioned by name in contemporary reports and there are no further references to Carter after 1749.
